SentinelFlight Phase 5 -- OpenCV ArUco landing-pad perception vs. live SITL

Setup: WSL2 Ubuntu 22.04, ROS 2 Humble, PX4 SITL launched against the
bundled 'aruco' world with the x500_mono_cam_down vehicle
(PX4_GZ_WORLD=aruco HEADLESS=1 make px4_sitl gz_x500_mono_cam_down),
Micro XRCE-DDS Agent bridging PX4 uORB <-> ROS 2 DDS, ros_gz_bridge
bridging the Gazebo camera image into ROS 2, and the six-node stack
(camera bridge, landing_pad_detector_node, mission_manager_node,
safety_gate_node, offboard_controller, telemetry_logger_node) launched via
ros2 launch sentinel_flight_control mission.launch.py.

=== Marker identification (empirical, not assumed) ===

PX4-Autopilot's bundled Tools/simulation/gz/models/arucotag/arucotag.png
was swept against every standard cv2.aruco predefined dictionary with a
padded quiet zone (detection on the raw texture alone fails -- no quiet
zone; a real camera view of the ground plane naturally provides one).
Result: DICT_4X4_50, marker ID 0. Hardcoded as LandingPadDetector's
default.

=== Environment issues found and fixed, in order ===

1. WSL's apt python3-opencv (4.5.4) was broken: `import cv2` failed with
   a numpy 1.x/2.x ABI mismatch (pip's numpy 2.2.6 shadowing the apt
   numpy the system cv2 was built against). Fixed with
   `pip3 install 'numpy<2'`.
2. ros-humble-ros-gz (apt) was not installed; installed via
   `sudo apt install ros-humble-ros-gz`.
3. THE BIG ONE: the apt ros-humble-ros-gz-bridge package is linked
   against ignition-transport11 (the old 'Ignition' Gazebo Transport, pre-
   Harmonic), while this PX4 checkout's SITL runs Gazebo Sim 8.14.0
   (Harmonic) on gz-transport13. These are two separate, incompatible
   transport buses -- confirmed via `ldd libros_gz_bridge.so` showing
   libignition-transport11.so.11/libignition-msgs8.so.8. The bridge
   process would start, register a real ROS 2 publisher, and even show up
   in `gz topic -i` as a "subscriber" (actually just gz-sim's own loopback
   self-reference), but never actually receive a single frame -- `gz
   topic -e`/`gz topic -l` (built against the correct gz-transport13)
   worked fine the whole time, which is what made this a transport-layer
   mismatch rather than a Gazebo-side problem. Fixed by cloning
   github.com/gazebosim/ros_gz (humble branch) and building
   ros_gz_interfaces/ros_gz_bridge/ros_gz_image from source with
   GZ_VERSION=harmonic against the already-installed libgz-sim8-dev/
   libgz-transport13-dev/libgz-msgs10-dev headers, then overlaying that
   workspace's install/setup.bash (--allow-overriding ros_gz_bridge
   ros_gz_image) after /opt/ros/humble in every shell that runs
   `ros2 launch`. Confirmed fixed: the rebuilt libros_gz_bridge.so links
   against libgz-transport13.so.13/libgz-msgs10.so.10, and a subscriber
   address other than gz-sim's own loopback appeared in `gz topic -i`.

=== Design bug found via live testing, fixed before the good run ===

First mission-stack launch with real perception: SafetyGate hit
MISSION_ABORT (status 8, state 4, "Repeated unsafe commands from mission
planner") within seconds of arming, during ordinary SEARCH-phase hover.
Cause: safety_gate_node forwarded raw perception confidence to
AIStatus.confidence *whenever a marker was merely visible*, even at
long range/small-in-frame (~0.15-0.4 confidence while still climbing to
5m) -- well below SafetyGate.land_confidence_threshold (0.50), and well
before MissionManager's own APPROACH_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD (0.80) would
ever act on it. Five consecutive low-confidence ticks (0.5s at 10Hz)
permanently aborted a mission that was never actually depending on that
detection. Fixed: added /sentinelflight/mission_trusting_perception
(std_msgs/Bool, published by mission_manager_node, true only in
APPROACH_TARGET/ALIGN/DESCEND/LAND); safety_gate_node now only forwards
real perception confidence when that's true, else the same
NO_TARGET_AI_CONFIDENCE=0.95 placeholder used when no target is detected
at all.

=== Verified run (post-fix) ===

ros2 topic echo /sentinelflight/perception_status --once (during climb):
  target_detected: true
  confidence: 0.15135633945465088
  center_x_offset: -0.0054687499068677425
  center_y_offset: 0.012500000186264515
  (real ArUco detection against the live Gazebo camera feed -- the
  detector genuinely sees and localizes the marker)

ros2 topic echo /sentinelflight/safety_event --once (same period):
  status: 0        (APPROVED)
  state: 0         (NORMAL)
  reason: OK
  ai_confidence: 0.949999988079071
  failsafe_active: false
  (confirms the mission_trusting_perception fix: real low-confidence
  detection during SEARCH no longer trips the gate)

No false MISSION_ABORT during SEARCH-phase hover this run (unlike the
pre-fix attempt). offboard_controller's hold-duration fallback timer
triggered AUTO_LAND at ~5m after the usual hold period (MissionManager
never crossed the 0.80 APPROACH_TARGET threshold while holding steady at
the 5m SEARCH altitude -- see "Confidence heuristic calibration" below).

As PX4's AUTO_LAND then physically descended the vehicle, the marker grew
in-frame and perception confidence rose with it. MissionManager --
still evaluating every tick against the real, falling vehicle_z and
rising confidence -- followed along through APPROACH_TARGET -> ALIGN ->
DESCEND -> LAND on its own (confirmed:
/sentinelflight/mission_land_requested flipped true). This is a genuine,
live confirmation that the full state-machine chain and its confidence
thresholds work end-to-end -- just triggered by PX4's own descent rather
than a MissionManager-commanded one, since offboard_controller had
already handed off to AUTO_LAND by that point.

During that same descent, confidence fluctuated enough (real camera
noise/vehicle motion, unsmoothed area-based heuristic) to trip
SafetyGate's max_consecutive_rejections=5 a second time -- correctly and
intentionally, this time (MissionManager really was depending on
perception at that point) -- resulting in a second, real MISSION_ABORT
that then persisted (SafetyState.MISSION_ABORT never auto-recovers) for
the remainder of the flight. See "Confidence heuristic calibration"
below.

